      Activism
   =20
 =20

In a proxy fight, an activist shareholder tries to take over the board of d=
irectors of a public company, or at least get some of her directors on the =
board. And the existing board of directors =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cmanagement,=
=E2=80=9D we call them=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0wants to stay on the board and k=
eep her candidates=C2=A0off, and there is an election and all the sharehold=
ers get to vote. If the activist=E2=80=99s candidates get more votes, her d=
irectors get on the board, and they can try to make the company implement h=
er plans.
  [2]
 If management gets more votes, then the activist goes away.
One weird thing about this contest is that management sets the rules for th=
e contest. The rules for director elections are set in the company=E2=80=99=
s bylaws, and the board generally writes the bylaws and can change them whe=
never it wants. And so if an activist shareholder shows up and wants to run=
 a proxy fight, the existing board of directors can say =E2=80=9Canyone who=
 wants to run for director must write a disclosure statement that explains =
in detail where they were every hour of the last 20 years, and they must wr=
ite it in gold ink on paper woven from unicorns=E2=80=99 manes, and they mu=
st have it hand-delivered to the company=E2=80=99s office=C2=A0by the third=
 son of the second daughter of the third cousin twice removed of the Prince=
 of Thurn und Taxis at midnight on a night when the moon is full, but the o=
ffice will be closed because it=E2=80=99s midnight. Except that the board c=
an waive this requirement for management nominees.=E2=80=9D And then manage=
ment=E2=80=99s directors get re-nominated for the board, and the activist n=
ominates her candidates, and management says =E2=80=9Coh no sorry there is =
some non-unicorn-mane content in this paper, we must regretfully reject you=
r nomination,=E2=80=9D and there is no proxy fight and the management direc=
tors remain in charge.
Well, really, then the hedge fund goes to court in Delaware =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
where most US public companies are incorporated and most governance dispute=
s are heard =E2=80=94=C2=A0and sues, arguing that the bylaw is invalid beca=
use it is designed only to entrench management. And then management comes t=
o court and says =E2=80=9Cno this bylaw is very important, if shareholders =
don=E2=80=99t know where all the director nominees were every hour then how=
 will they know if the activist=E2=80=99s nominees were hatching secret plo=
ts to undermine long-term investment in the company.=E2=80=9D And then they=
 argue in court about whether the bylaws are mostly designed to (1) help sh=
areholders make informed voting decisions about who should run the company =
or (2) stop activists by making it impossible for them to nominate director=
s. And obviously the answer is always =E2=80=9Cboth=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the bylaws have the effect both of giving shareholders more information =
and of making proxy fights more difficult, and management has both goals =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0so it=E2=80=99s always a bit of a mess.
Here=E2=80=99s Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Scott Deveau on a   director-nomination-=
bylaw fight:

The activist investor pushing for board seats at Masimo Corp. has filed a l=
awsuit to reverse what it called a series of =E2=80=9Cdraconian=E2=80=9D me=
asures adopted by the medical device company.
Politan Capital Management, which owns an 8.9% stake in Masimo, contends th=
ose measures are a deterrent to nominating directors and could more broadly=
 chill shareholder activism if others follow suit. Politan is asking a Dela=
ware Chancery Court judge to throw out amendments to Masimo=E2=80=99s bylaw=
s adopted last month, along with some change-of-control provisions. ...
The measures adopted by Masimo are the latest iteration of the cat-and-mous=
e tactics deployed by activists and the defense advisers hired by the compa=
nies they target. It follows a regulatory change in September providing for=
 a so-called universal proxy card, which allows stockholders to pick and ch=
oose from the directors nominated by management or an activist, rather than=
 vote for one entire slate or the other.
The universal proxy card was meant to make nominating directors easier and =
less expensive for shareholders, said Larry Cunningham, a professor of corp=
orate governance at George Washington University Law School. He said the me=
asures adopted by Masimo in response were some of the most =E2=80=9Cextreme=
=E2=80=9D he=E2=80=99s seen.=C2=A0
Masimo requires shareholders nominating directors to disclose some of the i=
nvestors in their own funds. Its bylaws also now require dissidents to disc=
lose their investors=E2=80=99 holdings in other companies and even those of=
 their family members. Politan argues that some investors =E2=80=9Cwould be=
 unwilling, unable or contractually prohibited from disclosing=E2=80=9D tha=
t information.

Here is  the bylaw, which requires an activist hedge fund to provide disclo=
sures not just about the hedge fund=E2=80=99s holdings, but also about the =
fund=E2=80=99s limited partners=E2=80=99 holdings. If an activist fund gets=
 more than 5% of its capital from any investor, the bylaw requires the fund=
 to disclose that investor=E2=80=99s name and address and a bunch of inform=
ation about its investments, including its investments in any competitor of=
 Masimo.  Politan=E2=80=99s lawsuit explains that that=E2=80=99s not really=
 how things are done:

First, at the most basic level, the Covered Persons Disclosures contravene =
well-established norms of confidentiality in the investment fund industry b=
y requiring investment fund stockholders to disclose the names of their lim=
ited partners to Masimo.=C2=A0=C2=A0The identities of an investment fund=E2=
=80=99s outside investors are among its most valuable trade secrets and pro=
prietary information.
Second, many institutional investors that allocate capital to investment fu=
nds (including but not limited to activist funds) require that their names =
and investment allocations be kept confidential unless disclosure is requir=
ed by law, rule, or regulation. =E2=80=A6
Third, because institutional investors do not want their names and allocati=
ons disclosed=E2=80=94even privately to Masimo=E2=80=94the Covered Persons =
Disclosures, which one would reasonably expect to be broadly adopted by pub=
lic companies, will make it exponentially harder for investment funds to ra=
ise capital from such investors. =C2=A0The end result would be significantl=
y less stockholder activism across all public companies.
Fourth, investment fund stockholders would reasonably be concerned about th=
e manner in which Masimo would use information about their limited partners=
. =C2=A0Disclosing the identities of those limited partners could expose th=
em to harassment or other pressure tactics by Masimo in an effort to inflic=
t damage on the nominating stockholder=E2=80=99s business relationships.
Fifth, it would be impossible, as a practical matter, for an investment fun=
d stockholder to comply with the Covered Persons Disclosures requirement. =
=C2=A0Investment funds generally do not have access to information concerni=
ng the other investments of their limited partners. =C2=A0As noted, in many=
 cases those limited partners include entities like sovereign wealth funds =
or pension funds, which themselves manage vast amounts of money.

An activist hedge fund is in a sense a way for big institutional investors =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0sovereign wealth funds, pensions, endowments =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
to outsource activism. If you are a giant investor, you will own a lot of s=
tocks of a lot of companies, and some of those companies will be mismanaged=
, and you will think =E2=80=9Cit would be good, for me, if some annoying ac=
tivist investor came in here and yelled at these managers and reduced their=
 pay and stopped them from doing bad acquisitions and fired them and fixed =
up the companies.=E2=80=9D But most of the companies are fine, and you will=
 want to have good relationships with them, and=C2=A0not=C2=A0be perceived =
as a scary annoying activist. If you put some money into activist funds,=C2=
=A0there will be activism. Someone will hold corporate managers to account =
and punish the ones who misuse shareholder money. It won=E2=80=99t technica=
lly be you; no one will get mad at you for being rude to corporate managers=
. But your money will support activism, and the existence of activism will,=
 you hope, keep all the corporate managers on their toes; they will be a bi=
t more hard-working and responsive to avoid an activist fight.
Except that now Masimo wants to force activists to disclose their investors=
, so that it can pressure those investors to stop supporting activism, so t=
hat there will be less activism. And, as Politan says, =E2=80=9Cone would r=
easonably expect=E2=80=9D this sort of bylaw =E2=80=9Cto be broadly adopted=
 by public companies,=E2=80=9D since no public company really wants to get =
into a proxy fight if it doesn=E2=80=99t have to. So the result would be th=
at it=E2=80=99s a lot harder to run an activist fund. Deveau:

=E2=80=9CThis would be a show-stopper in lots of cases, and I think they kn=
ow that,=E2=80=9D Cunningham said in an interview. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s=
 a very good chance that the Delaware courts would reject this as an invali=
d exercise of corporate power.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CIs this a thinly veiled attempt to stop activism?=E2=80=9D asked M=
ichael Klaunser, a Stanford Law School professor. =E2=80=9CNo. It=E2=80=99s=
 not veiled at all; it=E2=80=99s utterly clear.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

The other side of the argument is: If an activist hedge fund wants sharehol=
ders to vote for its candidates, the shareholders need to know who it=E2=80=
=99s working for. Masimo=E2=80=99s response to the lawsuit  says the expect=
ed things:

Politan claims this case is about actions that Masimo took to purportedly =
=E2=80=9Centrench its incumbent directors in office.=E2=80=9D It is not. Ra=
ther, this case is about a company=E2=80=99s ability to ensure that its sto=
ckholders are fully informed when making one of the most important decision=
s that they are asked to make=E2=80=94electing directors to sit on the boar=
d. In doing so, a company has every right to: (i) ensure its stockholders h=
ave comprehensive disclosure about stockholders waging proxy=C2=A0contests =
with undisclosed interests that may be antithetical to stockholders=E2=80=
=99 best interests, and (ii) preserve the long-term value of its business. =
=E2=80=A6
Because of Politan=E2=80=99s lack of transparency, Masimo had no way of kno=
wing whether: (i) the funders backing Politan had Masimo=E2=80=99s best int=
erests in mind; (ii) were Masimo=E2=80=99s business competitors or adverse =
litigants; (iii) were investors in Masimo=E2=80=99s business=C2=A0competito=
rs or adverse litigants; or (iv) were shorting Masimo stock. Indeed, the fa=
ct that Politan has =E2=80=9Csovereign entities=E2=80=9D as investors is pa=
rticularly concerning, given that there are a number of sovereign entities =
that do not respect=E2=80=94and have attempted to steal=E2=80=94intellectua=
l property belonging to U.S. companies. Politan=E2=80=99s deficient disclos=
ures gave Masimo no reason to believe that a director nominated by Politan =
would be faithful to the Company.

Incidentally, the way these sort of director-nomination bylaws work is that=
 they make it very hard for=C2=A0activists=C2=A0to nominate directors, by i=
mposing lots of disclosure requirements, but those requirements don=E2=80=
=99t apply to=C2=A0management=E2=80=99s=C2=A0director nominees.=C2=A0Polita=
n=E2=80=99s lawsuit points out that one of the current Masimo directors run=
s a fund that invests in Masimo=E2=80=99s competitors:

Indeed, while the Bylaw Amendments mandate that a nominating stockholder di=
sclose this information to Masimo, the Questionnaire for Director Nominees =
(the =E2=80=9CD&O Questionnaire=E2=80=9D) does not require any such expande=
d disclosure. =C2=A0Thus, incumbent Board members are not subject to the sa=
me disclosure requirement as are stockholder nominees.
This discrepancy is particularly notable given that one of the Director Def=
endants, Adam Mikkelson, manages an investment fund that, earlier this year=
, held a substantial investment in Masimo=E2=80=99s primary competitor (and=
 no investment in Masimo).=C2=A0=C2=A0That investment was not disclosed in =
Masimo=E2=80=99s public filings, including its proxy statement, which under=
scores that the Board does not=C2=A0believe such information is relevant or=
 material to Masimo=E2=80=99s stockholders. =C2=A0Rather, it is intended to=
 discourage investment fund stockholders from nominating candidates for ele=
ction to the Board.

Well, yes, it would be very=C2=A0annoying to disclose all this stuff, which=
 is why only the activists have to do it.

