Look I am not personally a guy who would carry a bathroom sink into the off=
ices of Twitter Inc. just so that I could tweet a video with the caption =
=E2=80=9CEntering Twitter HQ =E2=80=94 let that sink in!=E2=80=9D To me, th=
at seems like a lot of effort to go to to make a joke that has been made ma=
ny times before on social media.
That said, I=C2=A0am a guy who uses Twitter, and who recognizes that this i=
s the sort of joke that people make on Twitter. So when Elon Musk tweeted t=
hat joke yesterday, my reaction was (1) a groan but also (2) =E2=80=9Cthat=
=E2=80=99s the first time a Twitter user has ever been in that building.=E2=
=80=9D My theory about Twitter has always been that no one who works at Twi=
tter uses the product. Elon Musk=C2=A0absolutely=C2=A0uses the product. Elo=
n Musk showed up for his first (negative-second?) day of work as Twitter=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=A6  Chief Twit? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and he planned his arrival ar=
ound making a good tweet.
  [3]
 That is not something that would ever have occurred to Parag Agrawal. It i=
s not something that would ever have occurred to Jack Dorsey! Musk owns Twi=
tter =E2=80=94=C2=A0almost! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but he also=C2=A0uses=C2=A0Twitt=
er, he loves Twitter, he=E2=80=99s addicted to Twitter, he thinks about his=
 life in terms of making content for Twitter.
Is that a good sign for his reign as Chief Twit? Oh, who knows, probably no=
t; my other theory about Twitter is that it=E2=80=99s probably for the best=
 that no one who works there uses the product.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIf you put Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s most addicted users in charge,=E2=80=9D  I once wrote,=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cit would be an unusable nightmare of harassment and weirdness.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhy is the new CEO carrying a sink around,=E2=80=9D Twitter=
=E2=80=99s employees might reasonably ask, and the answer is =E2=80=9Che=E2=
=80=99s not the CEO, he=E2=80=99s the Chief Twit.=E2=80=9D Aren=E2=80=99t y=
ou tired of this already?
On the unusable-nightmare-of-harassment point, today Musk tweeted an open l=
etter to Twitter=E2=80=99s advertisers, promising not to make Twitter =E2=
=80=9Ca free-for-all hellscape.=E2=80=9D As an economic actor, Musk wants T=
witter not to be a hellscape, because advertisers don=E2=80=99t love a hell=
scape. As a believer that Twitter =E2=80=9Cis important to the future of ci=
vilization=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0as he also says in that open letter =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Musk=C2=A0also=C2=A0probably wants it not to be a hellscape, be=
cause=C2=A0users=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t love a hellscape either, and if Musk ta=
kes over Twitter and drives away all the users I am sure he will be sad. Bu=
t as an=C2=A0addicted Twitter troll, I suspect that Musk=C2=A0kind of=C2=A0=
wants it to be a hellscape? I assume that his better judgment as a business=
man and a philosopher will prevail. But if you just look at his personal Tw=
itter feed you might think, well, yes, a little hellish, sure.
Anyway the money is moving:

Banks have started to send $13 billion in cash backing Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =
takeover of Twitter Inc., according to people familiar with the matter, the=
 latest sign the $44 billion deal for the social-media company is on track =
to close by the end of the week after months of twists and turns.
Mr. Musk late Tuesday sent a so-called borrowing notice to the banks that a=
greed to provide him with the debt for the purchase, one of the people said=
. That kicked off a process that is currently under way by which banks will=
 deposit funds they are on the hook for into an escrow account after hammer=
ing out final details of the debt contracts, the people said.

We have  talked previously about Musk=E2=80=99s belief that =E2=80=9Cthe mo=
st entertaining outcome is the most likely,=E2=80=9D and I have given some =
suggestions for the most entertaining way for this to end. Arguably the mai=
n reason that Musk wanted to buy Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0and somehow also  t=
he reason he gave for trying to get out of the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0was that=
, as a hugely famous and rich public figure, he was beset by spam bots. Any=
 time he tweeted, people or bots would post weird replies generally trying =
to dupe readers into sending cryptocurrency to the spammers. =E2=80=9CI am =
doubling everyone=E2=80=99s money to give back to the community, send one=
=C2=A0Dogecoin to this address and I=E2=80=99ll send you back two,=E2=80=9D=
 the spammers would say, pretending to be Musk himself. That understandably=
 irritated Musk, and now here we are.
What I am saying here is that if Elon Musk=E2=80=99s banks were somehow dup=
ed into wiring $13 billion to a scammer, rather than into escrow to close t=
his deal,=C2=A0that would be the funniest possible outcome here. I assign i=
t a probability of zero, but if it somehow happened, I would enjoy it immen=
sely. I bet so would Musk. It=E2=80=99s good content!

