<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Activism</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a proxy fight, an activist shareholder trie=
s to take over the board of directors of a public company, or at least get =
some of her directors on the board. And the existing board of directors =E2=
=80=94 =E2=80=9Cmanagement,=E2=80=9D we call them=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0wants=
 to stay on the board and keep her candidates=C2=A0off, and there is an ele=
ction and all the shareholders get to vote. If the activist=E2=80=99s candi=
dates get more votes, her directors get on the board, and they can try to m=
ake the company implement her plans.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If management gets more votes, then the activist goes away.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One weird thing about this contest is that man=
agement sets the rules for the contest. The rules for director elections ar=
e set in the company=E2=80=99s bylaws, and the board generally writes the b=
ylaws and can change them whenever it wants. And so if an activist sharehol=
der shows up and wants to run a proxy fight, the existing board of director=
s can say =E2=80=9Canyone who wants to run for director must write a disclo=
sure statement that explains in detail where they were every hour of the la=
st 20 years, and they must write it in gold ink on paper woven from unicorn=
s=E2=80=99 manes, and they must have it hand-delivered to the company=E2=80=
=99s office=C2=A0by the third son of the second daughter of the third cousi=
n twice removed of the Prince of Thurn und Taxis at midnight on a night whe=
n the moon is full, but the office will be closed because it=E2=80=99s midn=
ight. Except that the board can waive this requirement for management nomin=
ees.=E2=80=9D And then management=E2=80=99s directors get re-nominated for =
the board, and the activist nominates her candidates, and management says =
=E2=80=9Coh no sorry there is some non-unicorn-mane content in this paper, =
we must regretfully reject your nomination,=E2=80=9D and there is no proxy =
fight and the management directors remain in charge.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, really, then the hedge fund goes to cour=
t in Delaware =E2=80=94=C2=A0where most US public companies are incorporate=
d and most governance disputes are heard =E2=80=94=C2=A0and sues, arguing t=
hat the bylaw is invalid because it is designed only to entrench management=
. And then management comes to court and says =E2=80=9Cno this bylaw is ver=
y important, if shareholders don=E2=80=99t know where all the director nomi=
nees were every hour then how will they know if the activist=E2=80=99s nomi=
nees were hatching secret plots to undermine long-term investment in the co=
mpany.=E2=80=9D And then they argue in court about whether the bylaws are m=
ostly designed to (1) help shareholders make informed voting decisions abou=
t who should run the company or (2) stop activists by making it impossible =
for them to nominate directors. And obviously the answer is always =E2=80=
=9Cboth=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bylaws have the effect both of giving s=
hareholders more information and of making proxy fights more difficult, and=
 management has both goals =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it=E2=80=99s always a bit of a=
 mess.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Scott Devea=
u on a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29512677.28=
9504/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMjEvbW=
FzaW1vLWludmVzdG9yLXBvbGl0YW4tc3Vlcy10by1ibG9jay1ydWxlcy1oaW5kZXJpbmctYWN0a=
XZpc3RzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB854abbd0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  director-nomination-bylaw figh=
t</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The activist investor pushing for board seats =
at Masimo Corp. has filed a lawsuit to reverse what it called a series of =
=E2=80=9Cdraconian=E2=80=9D measures adopted by the medical device company.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Politan Capital Management, which owns an 8.9%=
 stake in Masimo, contends those measures are a deterrent to nominating dir=
ectors and could more broadly chill shareholder activism if others follow s=
uit. Politan is asking a Delaware Chancery Court judge to throw out amendme=
nts to Masimo=E2=80=99s bylaws adopted last month, along with some change-o=
f-control provisions. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The measures adopted by Masimo are the latest =
iteration of the cat-and-mouse tactics deployed by activists and the defens=
e advisers hired by the companies they target. It follows a regulatory chan=
ge in September providing for a so-called universal proxy card, which allow=
s stockholders to pick and choose from the directors nominated by managemen=
t or an activist, rather than vote for one entire slate or the other.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The universal proxy card was meant to make nom=
inating directors easier and less expensive for shareholders, said Larry Cu=
nningham, a professor of corporate governance at George Washington Universi=
ty Law School. He said the measures adopted by Masimo in response were some=
 of the most =E2=80=9Cextreme=E2=80=9D he=E2=80=99s seen.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Masimo requires shareholders nominating direct=
ors to disclose some of the investors in their own funds. Its bylaws also n=
ow require dissidents to disclose their investors=E2=80=99 holdings in othe=
r companies and even those of their family members. Politan argues that som=
e investors =E2=80=9Cwould be unwilling, unable or contractually prohibited=
 from disclosing=E2=80=9D that information.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29512677.289504/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9l=
ZGdhci9kYXRhLzkzNzU1Ni8wMDAxMTA0NjU5MjIwOTg3MDQvdG0yMjI1MTMyZDFfZXgzLTIuaHR=
t/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10692b94" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the bylaw</a>, which requires=
 an activist hedge fund to provide disclosures not just about the hedge fun=
d=E2=80=99s holdings, but also about the fund=E2=80=99s limited partners=E2=
=80=99 holdings. If an activist fund gets more than 5% of its capital from =
any investor, the bylaw requires the fund to disclose that investor=E2=80=
=99s name and address and a bunch of information about its investments, inc=
luding its investments in any competitor of Masimo. <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29512677.289504/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvd=
i9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzkzNzU1Ni8wMDAwOTE0MTIxMjIwMDQxMjUvcG81ODMxNTU1=
MS1leDk5XzQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61eab886" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Politan=E2=80=
=99s lawsuit</a> explains that that=E2=80=99s not really how things are don=
e:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, at the most basic level, the Covered Pe=
rsons Disclosures contravene well-established norms of confidentiality in t=
he investment fund industry by requiring investment fund stockholders to di=
sclose the names of their limited partners to Masimo.=C2=A0=C2=A0The identi=
ties of an investment fund=E2=80=99s outside investors are among its most v=
aluable trade secrets and proprietary information.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, many institutional investors that allo=
cate capital to investment funds (including but not limited to activist fun=
ds) require that their names and investment allocations be kept confidentia=
l unless disclosure is required by law, rule, or regulation. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, because institutional investors do not =
want their names and allocations disclosed=E2=80=94even privately to Masimo=
=E2=80=94the Covered Persons Disclosures, which one would reasonably expect=
 to be broadly adopted by public companies, will make it exponentially hard=
er for investment funds to raise capital from such investors. =C2=A0The end=
 result would be significantly less stockholder activism across all public =
companies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fourth, investment fund stockholders would rea=
sonably be concerned about the manner in which Masimo would use information=
 about their limited partners. =C2=A0Disclosing the identities of those lim=
ited partners could expose them to harassment or other pressure tactics by =
Masimo in an effort to inflict damage on the nominating stockholder=E2=80=
=99s business relationships.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fifth, it would be impossible, as a practical =
matter, for an investment fund stockholder to comply with the Covered Perso=
ns Disclosures requirement. =C2=A0Investment funds generally do not have ac=
cess to information concerning the other investments of their limited partn=
ers. =C2=A0As noted, in many cases those limited partners include entities =
like sovereign wealth funds or pension funds, which themselves manage vast =
amounts of money.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An activist hedge fund is in a sense a way for=
 big institutional investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0sovereign wealth funds, pension=
s, endowments =E2=80=94=C2=A0to <em>outsource</em> activism. If you are a g=
iant investor, you will own a lot of stocks of a lot of companies, and some=
 of those companies will be mismanaged, and you will think =E2=80=9Cit woul=
d be good, for me, if some annoying activist investor came in here and yell=
ed at these managers and reduced their pay and stopped them from doing bad =
acquisitions and fired them and fixed up the companies.=E2=80=9D But most o=
f the companies are fine, and you will want to have good relationships with=
 them, and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>be perceived as a scary annoying activist=
. If you put some money into activist funds,=C2=A0<em>there will be activis=
m</em>. Someone will hold corporate managers to account and punish the ones=
 who misuse shareholder money. It won=E2=80=99t technically be you; no one =
will get mad at you for being rude to corporate managers. But your money wi=
ll support activism, and the existence of activism will, you hope, keep all=
 the corporate managers on their toes; they will be a bit more hard-working=
 and responsive to avoid an activist fight.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except that now Masimo wants to force activist=
s to disclose their investors, so that it can pressure those investors to s=
top supporting activism, so that there will be less activism. And, as Polit=
an says, =E2=80=9Cone would reasonably expect=E2=80=9D this sort of bylaw =
=E2=80=9Cto be broadly adopted by public companies,=E2=80=9D since no publi=
c company really wants to get into a proxy fight if it doesn=E2=80=99t have=
 to. So the result would be that it=E2=80=99s a lot harder to run an activi=
st fund. Deveau:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis would be a show-stopper in lots =
of cases, and I think they know that,=E2=80=9D Cunningham said in an interv=
iew. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a very good chance that the Delaware courts w=
ould reject this as an invalid exercise of corporate power.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIs this a thinly veiled attempt to st=
op activism?=E2=80=9D asked Michael Klaunser, a Stanford Law School profess=
or. =E2=80=9CNo. It=E2=80=99s not veiled at all; it=E2=80=99s utterly clear=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other side of the argument is: If an activ=
ist hedge fund wants shareholders to vote for its candidates, the sharehold=
ers need to know who it=E2=80=99s working for. Masimo=E2=80=99s response to=
 the lawsuit <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29512=
677.289504/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRm=
eElVL3JQT25BYXU3NWpvZy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB838c80a4" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says=
 the expected things</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Politan claims this case is about actions that=
 Masimo took to purportedly =E2=80=9Centrench its incumbent directors in of=
fice.=E2=80=9D It is not. Rather, this case is about a company=E2=80=99s ab=
ility to ensure that its stockholders are fully informed when making one of=
 the most important decisions that they are asked to make=E2=80=94electing =
directors to sit on the board. In doing so, a company has every right to: (=
i) ensure its stockholders have comprehensive disclosure about stockholders=
 waging proxy=C2=A0contests with undisclosed interests that may be antithet=
ical to stockholders=E2=80=99 best interests, and (ii) preserve the long-te=
rm value of its business. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because of Politan=E2=80=99s lack of transpare=
ncy, Masimo had no way of knowing whether: (i) the funders backing Politan =
had Masimo=E2=80=99s best interests in mind; (ii) were Masimo=E2=80=99s bus=
iness competitors or adverse litigants; (iii) were investors in Masimo=E2=
=80=99s business=C2=A0competitors or adverse litigants; or (iv) were shorti=
ng Masimo stock. Indeed, the fact that Politan has =E2=80=9Csovereign entit=
ies=E2=80=9D as investors is particularly concerning, given that there are =
a number of sovereign entities that do not respect=E2=80=94and have attempt=
ed to steal=E2=80=94intellectual property belonging to U.S. companies. Poli=
tan=E2=80=99s deficient disclosures gave Masimo no reason to believe that a=
 director nominated by Politan would be faithful to the Company.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally, the way these sort of director-n=
omination bylaws work is that they make it very hard for=C2=A0<em>activists=
</em>=C2=A0to nominate directors, by imposing lots of disclosure requiremen=
ts, but those requirements don=E2=80=99t apply to=C2=A0<em>management=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0</em>director nominees.=C2=A0Politan=E2=80=99s lawsuit points out=
 that one of the current Masimo directors runs a fund that invests in Masim=
o=E2=80=99s competitors:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indeed, while the Bylaw Amendments mandate tha=
t a nominating stockholder disclose this information to Masimo, the Questio=
nnaire for Director Nominees (the =E2=80=9CD&amp;O Questionnaire=E2=80=9D) =
does not require any such expanded disclosure. =C2=A0Thus, incumbent Board =
members are not subject to the same disclosure requirement as are stockhold=
er nominees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This discrepancy is particularly notable given=
 that one of the Director Defendants, Adam Mikkelson, manages an investment=
 fund that, earlier this year, held a substantial investment in Masimo=E2=
=80=99s primary competitor (and no investment in Masimo).=C2=A0=C2=A0That i=
nvestment was not disclosed in Masimo=E2=80=99s public filings, including i=
ts proxy statement, which underscores that the Board does not=C2=A0believe =
such information is relevant or material to Masimo=E2=80=99s stockholders. =
=C2=A0Rather, it is intended to discourage investment fund stockholders fro=
m nominating candidates for election to the Board.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, yes, it would be very=C2=A0<em>annoying =
</em>to disclose all this stuff, which is why only the activists have to do=
 it.</p>
